Here’s an updated, self-contained HTML file that **integrates your new path**, **deduplicates references globally** (no reference appears twice), and **boosts readability** (larger base font, tighter typographic scale, improved spacing/contrast). I kept every **unique** item; where your new plan overlapped with the earlier page, I merged them and placed **chapter pointers** in the most logical section to avoid repetition.

```html
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1" />
  <title>QFT Reading Path — Integrated, Minimal-Redundancy Plan</title>
  <meta name="description" content="An integrated, minimal-redundancy QFT reading path with chapter pointers, RG/BRST depth, QED/EW/QCD essentials, math foundations, and seminal papers." />
  <style>
    :root{
      --bg: #ffffff;
      --fg: #0b1220;
      --muted: #475569;
      --accent: #0ea5e9;
      --surface: #f8fafc;
      --border: #e2e8f0;
      --code: #111827;
      --mark-bg: #fff7ed;
      --mark-fg: #7c2d12;
      --shadow: 0 1px 2px rgba(2, 6, 23, 0.06), 0 10px 30px rgba(2, 6, 23, 0.07);
      --radius: 16px;
      --maxw: 980px;
      --lh: 1.7;
      --font-size: 18px;         /* Larger base font for readability */
      --h1: 2.15rem;
      --h2: 1.55rem;
      --h3: 1.2rem;
    }
    @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
      :root{
        --bg: #0b1020;
        --fg: #e7eaf0;
        --muted: #a2adbb;
        --accent: #38bdf8;
        --surface: #0f172a;
        --border: #1f2937;
        --code: #e7eaf0;
        --mark-bg: #3a2a00;
        --mark-fg: #fde68a;
        --shadow: 0 1px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.45), 0 10px 30px rgba(0,0,0,0.4);
      }
    }
    *{ box-sizing: border-box; }
    html, body{ height: 100%; }
    body{
      margin: 0;
      font: var(--font-size)/var(--lh) system-ui, -apple-system, Segoe UI, Roboto, Ubuntu, Cantarell, "Helvetica Neue", Arial, "Noto Sans", "Apple Color Emoji","Segoe UI Emoji";
      color: var(--fg);
      background: radial-gradient(1200px 800px at 20% -10%, rgba(56,189,248,0.08), transparent 55%),
                  radial-gradient(1000px 600px at 120% 10%, rgba(56,189,248,0.06), transparent 50%),
                  var(--bg);
      text-rendering: optimizeLegibility;
      -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
      -moz-osx-font-smoothing: grayscale;
    }
    header{
      position: sticky; top: 0; z-index: 20;
      backdrop-filter: blur(6px);
      background: color-mix(in oklab, var(--bg) 92%, transparent);
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    }
    .wrap{ max-width: var(--maxw); margin: 0 auto; padding: 16px 20px; }
    h1{ font-size: var(--h1); line-height: 1.2; margin: 0; letter-spacing: -0.02em; }
    .lead{ margin: 8px 0 0; color: var(--muted); font-size: 1.05rem; }
    main{
      max-width: var(--maxw); margin: 28px auto 80px; padding: 0 20px;
      display: grid; grid-template-columns: 280px 1fr; gap: 28px;
    }
    nav{
      position: sticky; top: 86px; align-self: start;
      background: var(--surface); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--radius);
      padding: 14px; box-shadow: var(--shadow);
    }
    nav .title{ font-weight: 800; font-size: 1rem; margin-bottom: 8px; letter-spacing: -0.01em; }
    nav a{
      color: var(--muted); text-decoration: none; display: block; font-size: 1rem;
      padding: 7px 8px; border-radius: 8px;
    }
    nav a:hover{ background: color-mix(in oklab, var(--accent) 15%, transparent); color: var(--fg); }
    section{
      background: var(--surface); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--radius);
      padding: 22px; box-shadow: var(--shadow); scroll-margin-top: 98px;
    }
    h2{ margin: 0 0 12px; font-size: var(--h2); letter-spacing: -0.01em; line-height: 1.25; }
    h3{ margin: 18px 0 8px; font-size: var(--h3); }
    p{ margin: 10px 0; }
    ul, ol{ margin: 10px 0 12px 22px; }
    li{ margin: 6px 0; }
    .badge{
      display: inline-block; font-size: 0.86rem; padding: 2px 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: 999px; background: color-mix(in oklab, var(--accent) 10%, var(--surface)); color: var(--fg);
      margin-left: 8px;
    }
    mark{ background: var(--mark-bg); color: var(--mark-fg); padding: 0 4px; border-radius: 4px; }
    .note{
      border-left: 4px solid var(--accent); background: color-mix(in oklab, var(--accent) 8%, var(--surface));
      padding: 10px 12px; border-radius: 8px; color: var(--fg);
    }
    details{ border: 1px dashed var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 10px 12px; background: color-mix(in oklab, var(--surface) 85%, transparent); }
    details + details{ margin-top: 8px; }
    summary{ cursor: pointer; font-weight: 700; color: var(--fg); }
    code{ font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, "Liberation Mono", monospace; color: var(--code); font-size: 0.95em; }
    .foot{ max-width: var(--maxw); margin: 36px auto; padding: 0 20px 42px; color: var(--muted); font-size: 0.96rem; }
    .toplink{ text-decoration: none; color: var(--accent); font-weight: 700; }
    @media (max-width: 980px){
      main{ grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
      nav{ position: relative; top: 0; }
    }
    @media print{
      header, nav, .foot{ display: none; }
      body{ background: #fff; }
      section{ box-shadow: none; border-color: #ddd; }
      a{ color: #000; text-decoration: none; }
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <header>
    <div class="wrap">
      <h1>Structured QFT Reading Path <span class="badge">Integrated · Minimal Redundancy</span></h1>
      <p class="lead">Pick one “core” text per stage and use companions selectively. Physics and math are grouped so concepts and foundations develop together.</p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main>
    <nav aria-label="Table of contents">
      <div class="title">On this page</div>
      <a href="#spine">Core QFT Spine (with chapter pointers)</a>
      <a href="#rg">Renormalization &amp; RG (incl. anomalies)</a>
      <a href="#brst">Gauge Fixing, Ghosts, BRST</a>
      <a href="#qed">QED (basics → precision)</a>
      <a href="#qcd">QCD Essentials</a>
      <a href="#ew">Electroweak Theory</a>
      <a href="#eft">Effective Field Theory</a>
      <a href="#math">Mathematical Foundations</a>
      <a href="#papers">Seminal Papers (canonical)</a>
      <a href="#sequence">How to Use This List</a>
      <a href="#refs">Handy Reference / Overview</a>
      <a href="#modern">Optional Modern Methods</a>
      <a href="#addons">Optional but High-Yield Add-ons</a>
      <a href="#minimal">Minimal One-Book Path</a>
    </nav>

    <article>
      <!-- CORE SPINE (merged, with chapter pointers; no duplicates elsewhere) -->
      <section id="spine" aria-labelledby="spine-h2">
        <h2 id="spine-h2">Core QFT Spine <small class="badge">do one thoroughly; skim 1–2 companions</small></h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Peskin &amp; Schroeder, <em>An Introduction to QFT</em></strong> (1995) — <em>Ch. 2–7</em> (scalar/QED basics), <em>9–12</em> (renormalization), <em>15–16</em> (path integrals &amp; gauge fixing), <em>17–21</em> (non-Abelian gauge theory &amp; QCD intro). Exercises are collider/QCD-calibrated.</li>
          <li><strong>Schwartz, <em>Quantum Field Theory and the Standard Model</em></strong> (2014) — Parts I–II (modern renormalization/LSZ), Part III (gauge theories), Part IV (EW), Part V (QCD: running, factorization, PDFs, anomalies).</li>
          <li><strong>Weinberg, <em>The Quantum Theory of Fields</em>, Vol. I–II</strong> (1995–96) — Axiomatic/symmetry-first: Vol. I <em>Ch. 5–12</em> (symmetries, S-matrix, renormalization); Vol. II <em>Ch. 15–22</em> (non-Abelian gauge theory, anomalies, BRST). Use for conceptual checks.</li>
          <li><strong>Srednicki, <em>QFT</em></strong> (2007) — Modular chapters; clean renormalization and EFT presentation (use as a companion for clarity and path-integral conventions).</li>
          <li><strong>Zee, <em>QFT in a Nutshell</em></strong> — Rapid intuition and breadth (not a problem-book).</li>
          <li><strong>Tong, QFT lecture notes</strong> — Free, clear; excellent for first pass and revision.</li>
          <li><strong>Aitchison &amp; Hey, <em>Gauge Theories in Particle Physics</em>, Vol. 1–2</strong> (4th ed.) — Pedagogically excellent ramp; especially for EWSB and QCD phenomenology.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="note">This spine centralizes all core-text appearances so later sections can reference it without repeating titles.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- RG / RENORMALIZATION (merged) -->
      <section id="rg" aria-labelledby="rg-h2">
        <h2 id="rg-h2">Renormalization &amp; RG (and anomalies) <small class="badge">close the loop conceptually</small></h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Collins, <em>Renormalization</em></strong> (1984) — Conceptual + proof-heavy; MS scheme, OPE, factorization.</li>
          <li><strong>Zinn-Justin, <em>QFT and Critical Phenomena</em></strong> (4th ed.) — Wilsonian RG perspective; map relevant sections to gauge theories.</li>
          <li><strong>Georgi, <em>Lie Algebras in Particle Physics</em></strong> (2nd ed.) — Minimal but sufficient group theory for SU(2)×U(1), SU(3), reps, anomalies, model-building hygiene.</li>
          <li><strong>Itzykson &amp; Zuber, <em>Quantum Field Theory</em></strong> (1980) — Chapter pointers in QED below; also a broad reference on dim. reg. and loop techniques.</li>
          <li><strong>Bogoliubov &amp; Shirkov, <em>Introduction to the Theory of Quantized Fields</em></strong> — Axiomatic/renormalization classic.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- BRST / GAUGE FIXING (merged) -->
      <section id="brst" aria-labelledby="brst-h2">
        <h2 id="brst-h2">Gauge Fixing, Ghosts, and BRST <small class="badge">focused consolidation</small></h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Weinberg, <em>QToF</em> Vol. II</strong> — BRST chapters (concise, rigorous).</li>
          <li><strong>Henneaux &amp; Teitelboim, <em>Quantization of Gauge Systems</em></strong> — Standard reference.</li>
          <li><strong>Piguet &amp; Sorella, <em>Algebraic Renormalization</em></strong> — Anomalies/renormalization in gauge theories.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- QED (merged; no repeats from spine) -->
      <section id="qed" aria-labelledby="qed-h2">
        <h2 id="qed-h2">QED: from basics to precision <small class="badge">chapters &amp; context</small></h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Spine cross-refs</strong> — Use <em>P&amp;S</em> (Ch. 2–7, 9–12) or <em>Schwartz</em> (Parts I–II) for core QED + renormalization. <em>Srednicki</em> (Ch. 33–44) for crisp path-integral conventions.</li>
          <li><strong>Itzykson &amp; Zuber, <em>QFT</em></strong> — <em>Ch. 6–8</em> (spinor QED, Ward identities, vacuum polarization); surgical derivations.</li>
          <li><strong>Schweber, <em>QED and the Men Who Made It</em></strong> — Historical narrative clarifying the role of Ward–Takahashi identities, Dyson/Schwinger/Feynman/Tomonaga.</li>
          <li><strong>Berestetskii, Lifshitz, Pitaevskii, <em>Quantum Electrodynamics</em></strong> (LL Vol. 4) — Compact, precise reference.</li>
          <li><strong>Greiner &amp; Reinhardt, <em>QED of Strong Fields</em></strong> — Bound states/strong-field focus.</li>
          <li><strong>Weinberg, <em>QToF</em> Vol. I–II</strong> — IR issues, KLN/Bloch–Nordsieck, asymptotics (use as conceptual check).</li>
          <li><strong>Aoyama <em>et&nbsp;al.</em></strong> — Review of electron (g-2) theory (for what “precision QED” entails).</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- QCD (merged; avoid repeating spine titles except as cross-ref) -->
      <section id="qcd" aria-labelledby="qcd-h2">
        <h2 id="qcd-h2">QCD Essentials <small class="badge">running · factorization · collider basics · nonperturbative</small></h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Spine cross-refs</strong> — <em>P&amp;S</em> (Ch. 17–21) and <em>Schwartz</em> (Part V) for non-Abelian gauge theory, asymptotic freedom, factorization, PDFs.</li>
          <li><strong>Ellis, Stirling &amp; Webber, <em>QCD and Collider Physics</em></strong> — Ch. 1–5, 7–9: perturbative QCD, parton model, factorization, jets, event shapes.</li>
          <li><strong>Collins, <em>Foundations of Perturbative QCD</em></strong> — Factorization/OPE/SCET perspective.</li>
          <li><strong>Sterman, <em>An Introduction to QFT</em></strong> — Factorization and resummation at a rigorous level (selected chapters).</li>
          <li><strong>Lattice</strong> — Gattringer &amp; Lang, <em>QCD on the Lattice</em>; or Rothe, <em>Lattice Gauge Theories</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>Confinement/Chiral symmetry</strong> — Greensite, <em>An Introduction to the Confinement Problem</em>; Polyakov, <em>Gauge Fields and Strings</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>Chiral perturbation theory</strong> — Scherer &amp; Schindler, <em>A Primer for ChPT</em>; Pich, EFT notes.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- ELECTROWEAK (merged; avoid repeating spine titles except as cross-ref) -->
      <section id="ew" aria-labelledby="ew-h2">
        <h2 id="ew-h2">Electroweak Theory <small class="badge">SSB · Higgs · anomalies · precision</small></h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Spine cross-refs</strong> — <em>Schwartz</em> (Part IV) and <em>Weinberg Vol. II</em> for SSB, Goldstone theorem, anomalies, BRST.</li>
          <li><strong>Cheng &amp; Li, <em>Gauge Theory of Elementary Particle Physics</em></strong> — Clear full treatment: <em>Ch. 5–8</em> (Yang–Mills, SSB, Higgs), <em>Ch. 9–10</em> (EW phenomenology).</li>
          <li><strong>Quigg, <em>Gauge Theories of the Strong, Weak, and Electromagnetic Interactions</em></strong> (2nd ed.) — Conceptual overview with careful phenomenology; glue after Cheng–Li.</li>
          <li><strong>Aitchison &amp; Hey, Vol. 2</strong> — Pedagogical derivation of the EW sector, CKM, neutral currents, precision tests (S, T, U intuition).</li>
          <li><strong>Precision EW</strong> — Peskin &amp; Takeuchi (S,T,U), PDG EW review; Denner, <em>Techniques for the Calculation of EW Radiative Corrections</em> (advanced).</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- EFT (unchanged + integrated pointers) -->
      <section id="eft" aria-labelledby="eft-h2">
        <h2 id="eft-h2">Effective Field Theory <small class="badge">used across QED/QCD/EW</small></h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Petrov &amp; Blechman, <em>Effective Field Theories</em></strong> — Modern, practical across SM/BSM.</li>
          <li><strong>Manohar</strong>, TASI/lecture notes; <strong>Georgi</strong>, classic EFT notes.</li>
          <li><strong>SMEFT</strong> — Brivio &amp; Trott, “The Standard Model as an EFT” (comprehensive review).</li>
          <li><strong>SCET</strong> — Becher/Neubert or Stewart lecture notes (for resummation/factorization).</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- MATHEMATICAL FOUNDATIONS (merged; no duplication) -->
      <section id="math" aria-labelledby="math-h2">
        <h2 id="math-h2">Mathematical Foundations <small class="badge">study in parallel</small></h2>

        <h3>Lie groups, algebras, and representations</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Georgi, <em>Lie Algebras in Particle Physics</em></strong> — Particle-physics oriented (also listed in RG section as a conceptual companion).</li>
          <li><strong>Hall, <em>Lie Groups, Lie Algebras, and Representations</em></strong> — Mathematically clean.</li>
          <li><strong>Cvitanovic, <em>Group Theory: Birdtracks</em></strong> — Visual tensor methods, SU(N) mastery.</li>
          <li><strong>Slansky</strong>, “Group Theory for Unified Model Building” — Review with rep tables.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Geometry/topology of gauge fields</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Nakahara, <em>Geometry, Topology and Physics</em></strong> — Bundles, connections, Chern classes.</li>
          <li><strong>Frankel, <em>The Geometry of Physics</em></strong> — Differential forms approach; many examples.</li>
          <li><strong>Baez &amp; Muniain, <em>Gauge Fields, Knots and Gravity</em></strong> — Gentle intro to bundles/curvature.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Anomalies and index theorems</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Bertlmann, <em>Anomalies in QFT</em></strong> — Comprehensive.</li>
          <li><strong>Fujikawa &amp; Suzuki, <em>Path Integrals and Quantum Anomalies</em></strong> — Fujikawa method.</li>
          <li><strong>Bilal</strong>, “Lectures on Anomalies”; <strong>Harvey</strong>, TASI on anomalies — Clear notes.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Functional methods and rigor (optional)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Glimm &amp; Jaffe, <em>Quantum Physics: A Functional Integral Point of View</em></strong> — Constructive QFT.</li>
          <li><strong>Itzykson &amp; Zuber, <em>QFT</em></strong> — Reference-level breadth; dim. reg., loop tech (also cited under QED for specific chapters).</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- SEMINAL PAPERS (merged; all unique items retained) -->
      <section id="papers" aria-labelledby="papers-h2">
        <h2 id="papers-h2">Seminal Papers <small class="badge">short, canonical, worth reading</small></h2>

        <h3>QED / Renormalization</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Dyson</strong> (1949) — Series expansions &amp; renormalization structure.</li>
          <li><strong>Ward</strong> (1950); Ward–Takahashi identities — Current conservation ⇒ charge renormalization relations.</li>
          <li><strong>Schwinger</strong> (1948–51); <strong>Feynman</strong> (1949) — Foundational QED formalisms.</li>
          <li><strong>Kinoshita</strong> (1990s); <strong>Aoyama et&nbsp;al.</strong> (2010s) — Electron <em>g-2</em> state-of-the-art.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Yang–Mills &amp; Renormalizability</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Yang &amp; Mills</strong> (1954) — Non-Abelian gauge fields.</li>
          <li><strong>Faddeev–Popov</strong> (1967) — Ghosts and gauge fixing.</li>
          <li><strong>’t Hooft</strong> (1971); <strong>’t Hooft–Veltman</strong> (1972) — Renormalizability of non-Abelian gauge theories; dimensional regularization.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Electroweak Theory</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Glashow</strong> (1961) — SU(2)×U(1) electroweak idea.</li>
          <li><strong>Weinberg</strong> (1967); <strong>Salam</strong> (1968) — Spontaneously broken EW theory with masses.</li>
          <li><strong>Higgs</strong> (1964); <strong>Englert–Brout</strong> (1964); <strong>Guralnik–Hagen–Kibble</strong> (1964) — SSB mass generation.</li>
          <li><strong>Cabibbo</strong> (1963); <strong>Kobayashi–Maskawa</strong> (1973) — Flavor mixing and CPV (CKM).</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>QCD / Asymptotic Freedom / Scaling</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Gross &amp; Wilczek</strong> (1973); <strong>Politzer</strong> (1973) — Asymptotic freedom.</li>
          <li><strong>Altarelli &amp; Parisi</strong> (1977); <strong>Gribov–Lipatov</strong> (1972); <strong>Dokshitzer</strong> (1977) — DGLAP evolution (AP is highly readable).</li>
          <li><strong>Friedman–Kendall–Taylor</strong> (late 1960s) — DIS scaling data linking theory ↔ experiment.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Anomalies</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Adler</strong> (1969); <strong>Bell–Jackiw</strong> (1969) — Chiral anomaly (ABJ).</li>
          <li><strong>Bardeen</strong> (1969) — Anomaly structure/consistency in gauge theories.</li>
          <li><strong>Adler–Bardeen</strong> — Non-renormalization theorem.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- PRACTICAL SEQUENCE (merged) -->
      <section id="sequence" aria-labelledby="sequence-h2">
        <h2 id="sequence-h2">How to Use This List <small class="badge">practical, minimal detours</small></h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>One modern text end-to-end</strong>: Do <em>Schwartz</em> or <em>P&amp;S</em> (including problem sets). You’ll cover QED, renormalization, gauge fixing, beta functions.</li>
          <li><strong>Lock in EW</strong>: Read <em>Aitchison &amp; Hey (Vol. 2)</em> or <em>Cheng &amp; Li</em> on SSB/Higgs/currents/precision; then skim <em>Weinberg Vol. II</em> for the formal view.</li>
          <li><strong>QCD basics + phenomenology</strong>: Do <em>Ellis–Stirling–Webber</em> (Ch. 1–5, 7–9) on partons/running/factorization/jets; tie to <em>DGLAP</em> papers and <em>Gross–Wilczek/Politzer</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>Conceptual closure</strong>: Sample <em>Collins</em> (renormalization) and <em>Georgi</em> (group theory) to fill gaps: anomalies, BRST, representations.</li>
          <li><strong>Primary sources</strong>: Read <em>Weinberg (1967)</em>, <em>’t Hooft (1971/72)</em>, <em>Gross–Wilczek/Politzer (1973)</em>, <em>Altarelli–Parisi (1977)</em> with the textbooks open.</li>
        </ol>
        <details>
          <summary>Tips for picking a “core” and “companions”</summary>
          <ul>
            <li>Need worked collider examples fast → <strong>Schwartz</strong>; later add <strong>Ellis–Stirling–Webber</strong>.</li>
            <li>Want classic derivations + problem sets → <strong>P&amp;S</strong>; add <strong>Tong</strong> for clarity.</li>
            <li>Prefer modular chapters + clean renorm → <strong>Srednicki</strong>; reinforce with <strong>Collins</strong>.</li>
            <li>Intuition first → <strong>Zee</strong> as companion (not sole core).</li>
            <li>Formal precision/BRST/SSB → consult <strong>Weinberg</strong> selectively.</li>
          </ul>
        </details>
      </section>

      <!-- HANDY REFS -->
      <section id="refs" aria-labelledby="refs-h2">
        <h2 id="refs-h2">Handy Reference / Overview</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>PDG</strong> — <em>Review of Particle Physics</em> (up-to-date constants; concise topic reviews).</li>
          <li><strong>Thomson</strong>, <em>Modern Particle Physics</em> or <strong>Griffiths</strong>, <em>Introduction to Elementary Particles</em> — Fast phenomenology overview.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- MODERN METHODS -->
      <section id="modern" aria-labelledby="modern-h2">
        <h2 id="modern-h2">Optional Modern Methods</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Elvang &amp; Huang</strong>, <em>Scattering Amplitudes in Gauge Theory and Gravity</em> — On-shell methods.</li>
          <li><strong>Dixon</strong>, TASI lectures on scattering amplitudes — Concise notes.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- OPTIONAL ADD-ONS (new unique items) -->
      <section id="addons" aria-labelledby="addons-h2">
        <h2 id="addons-h2">Optional but High-Yield Add-ons</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Maggiore</strong>, <em>A Modern Introduction to QFT</em> — Streamlined path-integral pedagogy with clean exercises.</li>
          <li><strong>Dreiner, Haber, Martin</strong>, <em>Two-Component Spinor Techniques</em> (arXiv) — Clarifies chiral structures in EW/SUSY.</li>
          <li><strong>Pokorski</strong>, <em>Gauge Field Theories</em> — Compact, clear treatment of gauge theories and SSB.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- MINIMAL PATH (kept, points back to unique items only) -->
      <section id="minimal" aria-labelledby="minimal-h2">
        <h2 id="minimal-h2">Minimal One-Book Path</h2>
